               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390408-name-190" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-190" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-190" type="surname" value="GREENWOOD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390408-name-190" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES GREENWOOD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am clerk to William Gillmore Bolton and others—the prisoner was also a clerk of theirs. On the 3rd of April I left the office about three o'clock in the afternoon, leaving two cheques in my desk, one for 153<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 4<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. on the Bank of England, and the other on Gosling and Sharp for 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 8<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 1<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—I left the prisoner and another clerk in the office—I returned in about an hour, and missed the cheques—the pri<lb></lb>soner had then left the office—the desk had not been locked—I went, and</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183904080017"></xptr>
               <p>found him at his mother's in a state of intoxication—I searched his pocket, and took from it a bag containing ninety-nine sovereigns, and from a pocket-book five £5 notes and this small cheque, which was one of those we had lost—I went to the Bank, and found the other cheque there.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner. Q.</hi> What did you recover in all? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Upwards of 150<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—you were not prohibited from going to my desk.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
